title: Oil dips on well supplied markets despite tighter Iran sanctions
text: Oil prices inched lower on Wednesday on signs that global markets remain adequately supplied despite a jump to 2019 highs this week on Washington's push for tighter sanctions against Iran.

title: Why the Japanese don't buy American cars
text: U.S. automakers barely have a presence in Japan, the world's third-largest car market. Some blame protectionism, others cite the tastes of Japanese consumers and a lack of investment.

title: Why Warren Buffett says the newspaper business is 'toast'
text: Berkshire Hathaway CEO discusses the decline of the newspaper business and change in how readers get their information.

title: Wall Street's biggest bear says gains are all in for the year
text: Wells Fargo's Christopher Harvey says gains are in for the year. With CNBC's Melissa Lee and the Fast Money traders, Dan Nathan, Brian Kelly, Karen Finerman and Guy Adami.

title: Foxconn and Wisconsin are renegotiating their massive factory deal, governor's letter reveals
text: The disclosure comes in a letter from Governor Tony Evers to Foxconn executive Louis Woo, a special assistant to Chairman Terry Gou and the company's point person on the project.

title: Markets are at new highs, but the euphoria is missing
text: Stock traders do not view a new high as truly valid unless there is some serious action. And that is what is missing from the rally.

title: Barbara Corcoran  why being a bad student can help you succeed
text: Real estate mogul and star of the hit show, "Shark Tank," discusses how being a poor student does not determine how successful a person can be in the real world.

title: These Markets Are the Biggest Winners and Losers From Oil’s Rally
text: Emerging markets got a lift from the Federal Reserve, Donald Trump and Xi Jinping to start the year. Oil may be the next saving grace.

title: Market highs aren't backed up by economic fundamentals, says Gluskin Sheff's chief economist
text: David Rosenberg, chief economist and strategist at Gluskin Sheff, talks about the market highs with CNBC's "Closing Bell" team.

title: Melinda Gates On Marriage, Gender Equality & Solving Tough Problems
text: Melinda Gates is the cochair of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, which has committed over $45 billion to help solve some of the world's toughest problems. Melinda Gates believes the ultimate problem that needs solving is poverty.

title: We see good, investable opportunity in European stocks: CIO
text: David Herro, chief investment officer at Harris Associates, joins CNBC's "Closing Bell" to talk about how global markets are trading.

title: Cybersecurity is a real concern as companies profit off consumer data: Security expert
text: CNBC's "Power Lunch" team is joined by John Carlin, former assistant attorney general for the U.S. Department of Justice's National Security Division, to discuss how companies are selling consumer data.

title: We now know that OPEC has that spare capacity: Goldman's head of commodities research
text: Jeff Currie, global head of commodities research at Goldman Sachs, joins CNBC's "Power Lunch" team to talk about Goldman's call on oil.

title: 'We have a very strong economy that has a lot of legs', says  Saratoga CEO
text: Christian Oberbeck CEO of Saratoga Partners discusses why he thinks the United States economy is strong.

title: After Chilly Winter, Homebuilders To Share Earnings With High Hopes Ahead
text: The home building and home supply sectors are preparing to report Q1 results in coming weeks, but may have struggled in part due to chilly winter weather.

title: Former Uber executive on the company's IPO
text: Emil Michael, Former Uber Chief Business Officer, discusses the company's future, ridesharing and what investors should expect from Uber's IPO.

title: Pharma distributor Rochester Drug agrees to pay $20 million in first criminal opioid case
text: The indictment marked the first ever federal criminal charges against company executives for conspiring to illegally distribute opioids.

title: Americans working more than ever, here's how we got here
text: Oren Cass, Manhattan Institute, and Robert Frank, Cornell University, join 'The Exchange' to discuss 'workism,' the trend that has Americans working more hours.

title: LGBT groups and tech companies warn that a Texas bill could cost the state billions
text: The LGBTQ community and major employers say a bill passed by the Texas Senate is a license to discriminate, giving professionals the right to turn away people based on religious beliefs. Amazon, Dell, Apple and Facebook urged Texas to drop the bill.

title: Here's how to play energy infrastructure stocks
text: Michelle Johnston, senior managing director at Tortoise Capital Advisors, joins CNBC's "The Exchange" to discuss Tortoise's new fund that focuses on energy infrastructure.

title: S&P 500 breaks above all-time closing high
text: Art Cashin, director of floor operations at UBS, reacts to the S&P 500's march past its all-time closing high. CNBC's Carl Quintanilla, Morgan Brennan, Dom Chu and Bob Pisani report.

title: How To Get An Early Piece Of The Next Big IPO
text: Wish you could get in early before the next big tech IPO? If a call to the CEO falls flat, maybe Forge can help.

title: S&P 500 breaks above record closing high
text: The 'Fast Money Halftime Report' team discusses if the market can go onto new highs as the S&P 500 nears its record intraday high.

title: Very little sign of recession in US, says BNY Mellon Investment Management chief strategist
text: Alicia Levine, BNY Mellon Investment Management chief strategist, and CNBC's Bob Pisani on markets join 'The Exchange' to discuss markets and earnings they're watching.

title: Cannabis PR Firm Mattio Communications Completes Seed Round
text: Mattio Communications, a cannabis marketing company, said Tuesday it completed its seed round of funding that included a number of high profile venture capital firms.

title: Consumers may not have the right to anonymized data collected from them: Former FBI agent
text: Leo Taddeo, former FBI special agent in charge of the cyber division in New York, and CNBC's Leslie Picker join "Squawk Alley" to discuss how big box stores collect data to better market products and provide information to investors.

title: Trader Joe's tops list of best places to work
text: Aarthi Swaminathan of Yahoo Finance reports on the best large companies to work for and how employees value benefits and being happy at work.

title: Goldman's Hatzius Questions the Fed's Forecasting Edge
text: Jan Hatzius, chief economist at Goldman Sachs, examines the decline in the Federal Reserve's forecast outperformance relative to consensus. He speaks on "Bloomberg Daybreak: Americas.

title: Virtual Banking Offers a New and Different Proposition in HK, Says ZA International’s Xu
text: Apr.23 -- Wayne Xu, president of ZA International, discusses being a new face in the virtual banking sector, getting a virtual bank license in Hong Kong, the services that he’ll be offering, the capabilities he’s bringing to the table, the customers their trying to attract, the opportunities he’s seeing outside of China. He speaks exclusively to Yvonne Man and Stephen Lam on “Bloomberg Markets: Asia

title: Investors Debate the Market Melt-Up Narrative
text: Apr.23 -- Bob Michele, global chief investment officer and head of global fixed income at JPMorgan Asset Management, George Rusnak, co-head of global fixed income at Wells Fargo Investment Institute, and Peter Tchir, head of macro strategy at Academy Securities, discuss the positive factors that could lead to a market melt-up. They speak with Bloomberg's Jonathan Ferro on "Bloomberg Markets: The Open.

title: European Banks to Report Earnings: Here's What to Expect
text: Apr.23 -- European banks will probably get another urgent reminder why they need to rethink their strategies when they present results for the first quarter. Trading revenue, long a mainstay of earnings at big banks, will likely continue to slide and increase pressure on firms to shrink the business further.

title: Credit Suisse Sees a Turning Point in Global Economic Cycle
text: Neville Hill, chief European economist at Credit Suisse Securities, explains why he sees a potential sweet spot for markets and the global economy. He speaks with Bloomberg's Francine Lacqua on "Bloomberg Surveillance.

title: The Bubble Is in Private Equity in This Cycle, Longview CEO Says
text: Apr.23 -- Chris Watling, chief executive officer and chief market strategist at Longview Economics, examines the influence of private equity on this year's IPO market. He speaks with Bloomberg's Alix Steel on "Bloomberg Daybreak: Americas.

title: HSBC Is Still Bullish on This Market, Strategist Rasco Says
text: Jose Rasco, chief investment strategist at HSBC Private Bank Americas, and Conrad DeQuadros, senior economist and founding partner at RDQ Economics, discuss expectations for markets to climb higher on positive economic news. They speak with Bloomberg's Tom Keene on "Bloomberg Surveillance.

title: Alternative data comes of age, and investors are noticing
text: The ubiquity of the Internet of Things, coupled with improvements in data analytics means insights are available to investors earlier than ever. Mainstream investors are noticing.

title: DEMO: Skydeck (UC Berkeley) at TC Sessions: Robotics+AI
text: Caroline Winnett of Berkeley Skydeck introduces the latest creations from KiwiBot and Squishy Robotics

title: Algorithmic Trading: What It Means For Stock Market Volatility And Individual Investors
text: When the stock market turns volatile, algorithmic trading often gets the blame. Here's what investors need to know about algo trading and how it works.

title: It remains to be seen how Uber and Lyft will be successful: The Verge's Casey Newton
text: Casey Newton of The Verge and Steve Vassallo of Foundation Capital join CNBC's "Squawk Alley" to discuss Lyft and Uber valuations as the companies go public. Both companies are still reporting losses.

title: Ken Fisher: 'People should always think global first'
text: Billionaire and Founder of Fisher Investments Ken Fisher discusses IPO investing what areas of the market are attractive.

title: Another Covered Call ETF Arrives
text: Writing covered calls is a popular options strategy used by income investors. Also known as a “buy-write” strategy, covered calls involve selling call options on a stock the investor already owns.

title: Oil prices at nearly 6-month high after US announces sanctions
text: OPIS Global Head of Energy Analysis Tom Kloza on the outlook for oil prices.

title: Wealthfront's new high-yield accounts bring in $1 billion in just a few months
text: Wealthfront's high-yield cash account has attracted $1 billion from customers since launching in February.

title: Autonomous aircraft designed for 'ultra-endurance' flights reaches milestone
text: A self-sufficient autonomous aircraft that could potentially embark on flights of an indefinite length has reached a development milestone, academics said on Tuesday.

title: New home sales rise 4.5% in March
text: March home sales numbers point to a stronger housing market going forward. CNBC's Rick Santelli and Diana Olick report.

title: Market opens slightly higher following strong earnings reports
text: CNBC's Bob Pisani looks ahead at the day's market action.

title: KeepTruckin Rolls Into A $149M Series D Round
text: KeepTruckin, a trucking technology provider, today announced it secured $149 million in a Series D investment led by Greenoaks Capital, with participation from existing investors IVP, GV, Index Ventures and Scale Venture Partners.

title: The bull market started with a 'wall of worry' that hasn't subsided, says Leuthold's Jim Paulsen
text: Jim Paulsen, chief investment strategist at Leuthold Group, joins 'Squawk Box' to discuss Tuesday's earnings reports and whether there is room in the market for a surge.

title: Beyond Meat Gets Aboard the IPO Bandwagon
text: The plant-based meat maker has filed a revised S-1. It hopes to raise $184 million in its public debut.

title: How to fund your business
text: If you are looking to launch and fund a small business—you have options. Here's how to weigh and measure which route might be right for you.

title: AI Will Be A Vital Tool In Making The Global Economy More Sustainable And Efficient - PwC
text: Artificial intelligence can play a powerful role in making the global economy more sustainable, through better monitoring, predicting problems in advance, and enabling the more efficient use of resources.
